\par 
\par }\pard \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrdb\brdrw15\brsp20 \adjustright {
\par \page CHAPTER 21:
\par }\pard \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {Max Exist:
\par 
\par This controls how many of an item will be in world before an item will 
\par stop loading and before hunting code will be activated (if relevant).
\par This as well as structure and value are the key object values that most 
\par influence the mud economy.  Max_exist should be set according to how 
\par powerful an item is.  Simple items and general purpose items should be 
\par set unlimited (999).  Magic items of any power should be max_exist less 
\par than or equal to 5.  Super items should be set Max_exist=1  Other max_exist 
\par ranges are in the 20-30 range.
\par 
\par You should carefully examine The World for the max_exist of similar 
\par items in The World and set accordingly.  Make good use of LOW command and 
\par help files under policy.
\par 
\par 
\par NOTES:
\par 
\par RESTRICT ANY MAGIC ITEM:  You must set a limited max exist if you have 
\par set any form of apply other than simple AC.
\par 
\par SERIOUSLY RESTRICT ARTIFACT QUALITY ITEMS:  You must limit artifacts to 
\par less than 5 in world.
\par 
\par CONFORM YOUR MAX_EXISTS WITH ZONE FILE:  Your max exist should conform 
\par with your max exist in zone file.
\par 
\par CONFORM YOUR MAX_EXISTS WITH ZONE FILE PERCENT LOADS:  Low max_exist items
\par should *not* have hight percentage loads or load on a large number of 
\par mobs.  Simple math will show you if you have a max exist of 5 and you 
\par load it 40 percent of time on 12 different mobs, you will reach your max 
\par exist the first time some group clears a zone.  You should want your 
\par items to load sparingly for a long time or groups will just clear the 
\par zone the first week of production and then never come back.
\par 
\par }\pard \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrdb\brdrw15\brsp20 \adjustright {\page CHAPTER 22:
\par }\pard \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {Race and item sizing
\par 
\par The code does internal checks on item size and player size to determine if
\par a character can fit into an item.  Here's how the system works.
\par 
\par For any item worn (except neck, finger and wielded/held) it determines the
\par items percent size (%size).  Its %size is the ratio of its volume to a defined
\par 100% size.  The 100% sizes are as follows:
\par   head:   2500        waist:    4000
\par   body:  11000        back:     2500
\par   arm:    2000        leg:      6000
\par   wrist:   400        foot:     1600
\par   hand:    800
\par 
\par If the item is paired (pants), it doubles the 100% value before calculating
\par the %size.
\par 
\par Next it calculates the characters %height.  A character's %height is HEIGHT
\par divided by 70 inches (average human male height).
\par 
\par A character can wear the item provided:
\par 
\par 1.15 * %size > %height > %size * 0.85
\par 
\par The formula is actually this:
\par 
\par perc = height/70 * human-size
\par if vol > perc/0.85, too big
\par if vol < perc/1.15, too small
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par When MAKING objects, just do this.  Get the character that should be able to
\par wear its height, divide by 70.  Multiply this number by the 100% value listed
\par above and use the result as the objects volume.
\par 
\par NOTES:
\par 
\par PAIRED OBJECTS:  Remember to double volume
\par 
\par CONSISTENCY WITH MOB: Make sure the mob on which it will load is the 
\par right height to wear an object.
\par 
\par }\pard \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrdb\brdrw15\brsp20 \adjustright {CHAPTER 23:
\par }\pard \s15\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {Building Policies:
